Certainly! Below is an example of how you can create a TikZ diagram in LaTeX that represents the described graph with bold edges and dotted edges:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm,
                    every node/.style={circle, draw, fill=blue!30, text width=1.5em, align=center},
                    bold edge/.style={thick,->},
                    dotted edge/.style={dashed,->}]

    % Nodes
    \node (A) {A};
    \node (B) [below left of=A] {B};
    \node (C) [above right of=A] {C};
    \node (D) [below right of=B] {D};
    \node (E) [above left of=C] {E};

    % Edges
    \draw[bold edge] (A) -- (B);
    \draw[bold edge] (A) -- (C);
    \draw[dotted edge] (B) -- (C);
    \draw[dotted edge] (C) -- (D);
    \draw[dotted edge] (D) -- (E);

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **Nodes**: The nodes `A`, `B`, `C`, `D`, and `E` represent the vertices of the graph.
- **Edges**:
  - **Bold Edges**: Represented by the style `bold edge`. These edges are drawn using thick arrows (`thick, ->`) to indicate that they are expected to be present.
  - **Dotted Edges**: Represented by the style `dotted edge`. These edges are drawn using dashed lines (`dashed`) to indicate their implausibility.

You can customize the positions of the nodes and add more nodes and edges as needed for your specific graph. This template should give you a good starting point for creating your TikZ diagram.

